Reference-contexts: For controller architectures employing Q-learning, several thousand learning steps are not uncommon ([Kaelbling 92, Sutton 91]). Some researchers abandon experiments with robots for this reason, and resort to simulation ([Kaelbling 90]. Similarly, Multilayer Perceptrons | albeit having been used in robot control related applications (see, for instance, <ref> [Shepanski & Macy 87] </ref>) | show slow convergence rate and typically require several several hundred learning steps. The Pattern Associator, the associative memory used here, learns extremely fast; within a few learning steps meaningful associations between inputs and outputs develop.
